# Workflow

## Non-trivial work follows the SDD pattern

1. Check `specs/active/` for existing plans before acting on any feature.
2. For non-trivial work, invoke the `planner` subagent first — it writes `specs/active/[task-id]/plan.md` in isolation.
3. Invoke the `developer` subagent to implement against the plan.
4. Invoke the `verifier` subagent before marking anything done.

Trivial changes (typo fixes, single-line config changes) can skip the planner.

## Greenfield

This project is greenfield. Plans and implementations must not include migration paths, backfill steps, or backwards-compatibility logic. See `rules/greenfield.mdc`.

## No stub implementations

Never create stub implementations (placeholder handlers, `return codes.Unimplemented`, no-op functions). Implement functional behavior directly. For deferred or phased work, add explicit `// TODO:` comments in code and explicit TODO items in plans.

## Completion requires evidence

No "done" claims without running verification commands and checking their output. If a command hasn't been run in this session, you cannot claim it passes.

## Context hygiene

- Use the built-in `explore` subagent for codebase searches — not the main context.
- Use the built-in `shell` subagent for verbose shell sequences.
- Delegate deep reasoning and artifact creation to subagents.

## Build and verification

This repo is Go-only. Use the Go toolchain and Makefile:

- `go build -o bin/ ./cmd/...` — build all binaries
- `go test ./...` — run tests
- `go vet ./...` — static analysis
- `make all` — build, test, vet
- Prefer `Makefile` targets when available; use file-scoped commands for single packages (e.g. `go test ./internal/config/...`).
- External CLIs (`docker`, `kubectl`, `psql`, `golangci-lint`) may be invoked directly.

**Do not execute built binaries.** Verification uses unit tests, integration tests, `go vet`, and linters only. Running `./bin/...` or invoking compiled artifacts is disallowed to avoid arbitrary code execution. Test via `run(args, out, errOut)` seams and `go test`.

## Commit batching

When the user asks for commits, git history, or conventional commits:

- Use the `conventional-commits-and-batching` skill.
- Batch by theme (one reason per commit); prefer &lt;15 files per commit.
- For Go code, prefer dependency order: schema/proto → internal packages → cmd.
- Keep mechanical changes (formatting, renames) separate from functional ones.

## Security gate

Invoke `security-auditor` (read-only) whenever changes touch:

- Database schema or migrations
- VM lifecycle handlers, libvirt integration, or data-fetching logic
- Authentication, authorization, or credential handling
